questions.text:
Given this code:

const form = this.fb.nonNullable.group({
  username: ['', Validators.required],
  age: [0, Validators.min(18)]
});

What does nonNullable mean in this context?

Given this code:

form.get('email').setValidators([Validators.required, Validators.email]);
form.get('email').updateValueAndValidity();

Why is updateValueAndValidity() called after setValidators()?

Given this validator:

export function forbiddenValue(forbidden: string): ValidatorFn {
  return (control: AbstractControl): ValidationErrors | null => {
    return control.value === forbidden
      ? { forbiddenValue: { value: control.value } }
      : null;
  };
}

How would you apply this to a FormControl for the value 'admin'?

Given this route config:
{ path: 'dashboard', component: DashboardComponent, data: { title: 'Dashboard', breadcrumb: 'Home' } }

How do you access the static 'title' data in the component?

Given this interceptor:

export const cacheInterceptor: HttpInterceptorFn = (req, next) => {
  if (req.method !== 'GET') return next(req);
  const cached = cache.get(req.url);
  if (cached) return of(cached);
  return next(req).pipe(tap(res => cache.set(req.url, res)));
};

What is this interceptor doing?

Given this RxJS code:

const results$ = this.searchTerm$.pipe(
  debounceTime(400),
  distinctUntilChanged(),
  switchMap(term => this.searchService.search(term)),
  shareReplay(1)
);

What does shareReplay(1) add to this pipeline?

Given this code:

@Directive({ selector: '[appAutoFocus]' })
export class AutoFocusDirective implements AfterViewInit {
  constructor(private el: ElementRef) {}
  ngAfterViewInit() {
    this.el.nativeElement.focus();
  }
}

What does this directive do and why is ngAfterViewInit the correct lifecycle hook?

Given this pipe:

@Pipe({ name: 'timeAgo' })
export class TimeAgoPipe implements PipeTransform {
  transform(date: Date): string {
    const seconds = Math.floor((Date.now() - date.getTime()) / 1000);
    return seconds < 60 ? 'just now' : `${Math.floor(seconds / 60)} min ago`;
  }
}

Should this pipe be pure or impure, and why?

Given this test:

it('should call API on init', fakeAsync(() => {
  spyOn(service, 'getUsers').and.returnValue(of([]).pipe(delay(100)));
  fixture.detectChanges();
  tick(100);
  fixture.detectChanges();
  expect(component.users.length).toBe(0);
}));

Why is tick(100) called with 100?

Given this test:

const req = httpController.expectOne('/api/items');
req.flush([{ id: 1, name: 'Item' }]);
httpController.verify();

What does httpController.verify() do?

Given this code in a component using OnPush:

const result = await this.service.fetchData();
this.data = result;

Why might the template not update after this await?

Given this code:

@NgModule({
  declarations: [HighlightDirective],
  exports: [HighlightDirective]
})
export class SharedModule {}

Why must HighlightDirective be in both declarations and exports?

Given this test for a component with a form:

it('should disable submit when form is invalid', () => {
  component.form.get('email').setValue('');
  fixture.detectChanges();
  const btn = fixture.nativeElement.querySelector('button[type=submit]');
  expect(btn.disabled).toBeTrue();
});

For this test to pass, what must the template contain?
